{
  "texts": [
    "Further, achieving high spectral resolution often requires sacrificing spatial and temporal resolution, limiting its effectiveness in fields requiring detailed imaging, such as medical and agri-food monitoring (Villa et al. 2010; Fang et al. 2018).",
    "In scenarios where light is insufficient, the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of hyperspectral data presents an additional challenge.",
    "A low SNR can lead to unreliable data, affecting the accuracy of analyses and interpretations.",
    "This is particularly problematic in remote sensing, where signals from target objects are often weak (Chang 2022).",
    "Furthermore, managing and analyzing the substantial amount of data generated by HSI requires extensive computational resources and expertise, and the technology's sensitivity to environmental variations can affect data accuracy (Pu et al. 2015 (Pu et al., 2023;; Wendel and Underwood 2017)."
  ]
}